  "text": "[5] Still though, there are many styles of MVA and it is still not clear whether other MVA variants could be used to obtain more accurate estimates of propagation delay times. It is also important to consider the fact that the solar wind contains many types of structures including rotational discontinuities, tangential discontinuities, and interplanetary shocks. Tangential discontinuities are those that have no normal magnetic field crossing the plane that defines the discontinuity surface. These discontinuities convect passively with the solar wind. The orientations of tangential discontinuities are suitably studied using MVAB-0 or equivalently with our B ! ? MVA since the average IMF must be perpendicular to surface normal. On the other hand, the orientation of rotational discontinuities would not be as accurately estimated using MVAB-0 leading to degradation in the accuracy of propagation delay correction. The accuracy is also impacted by the fact that rotational discontinuities convect relative to the solar wind rest frame at velocities close to the Alfvén speed. Also, the direction of propagation would vary from case to case. Early studies found that rotational discontinuities are more common than tangential discontinuities in the interplanetary medium [i.e., [CITATION_1] . However, more recent work by [CITATION_2] , which was performed by using fourspacecraft Cluster data sets, contradicts the earlier studies and now suggests that tangential discontinuities are more prevalent. Still, a separate technique (besides MVAB-0) needs to be developed to account for the occurrence of rotational discontinuities in the solar wind. In the same way, shocks need to be handled as a separate class of events. Thus a set of tools including MVAB-0 needs to be assembled for the purpose of providing inclusive propagation delay correction.",
